            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@LarsH Function definitions are &lt;i&gt;are&lt;/i&gt; evaluated in Python. Whether that is from a statement (&lt;code&gt;def&lt;/code&gt;) or expression (&lt;code&gt;lambda&lt;/code&gt;) does not change that creating a function means evaluation -- especially of its signature. And defaults are part of a function&apos;s signature. That does not mean defaults &lt;i&gt;have&lt;/i&gt; to be evaluated immediately -- type hints may not, for example. But it certainly suggests they should unless there is a good reason not to.&lt;/span&gt;

